---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import { atlas } from '../../utils/atlas';
import { runJointLOO } from '../../utils/joint-prediction-eval';

const a = atlas();
const eval_ = runJointLOO();

function pct(num: number, den: number): string {
  if (den === 0) return 'n/a';
  return `${((num / den) * 100).toFixed(1)}%`;
}
function actorName(id: string): string {
  return a.actors.get(id)?.canonical_name ?? id;
}
function doctrineName(id: string): string {
  return a.doctrines.get(id)?.short_name ?? a.doctrines.get(id)?.name ?? id;
}
const perState = [...eval_.perState.entries()].sort((a, b) => b[1].scored - a[1].scored);
const generatedAt = eval_.generatedAt;
---
<Base title="Joint (actor × doctrine) prediction" wide>
  <p class="kicker">Research</p>
  <h1>Joint engine — actor × doctrine</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    Combines the actor-attribution and doctrine-prediction engines
    into a single ranking over <code>(actor, doctrine)</code> pairs.
    Joint score = log P(actor) + log P(doctrine) + log(1 + co-occurrence).
    The third term rewards pairs we've seen in training.
  </p>
  <p class="meta">Generated {generatedAt} · n={eval_.scored} events with both actor and doctrine labels</p>

  <section>
    <h2>Headline</h2>
    <div class="stat-grid">
      <div class="stat"><strong>{pct(eval_.hit1, eval_.scored)}</strong>top-1 pair hit</div>
      <div class="stat"><strong>{pct(eval_.hit3, eval_.scored)}</strong>top-3 pair hit</div>
      <div class="stat"><strong>{pct(eval_.hit5, eval_.scored)}</strong>top-5 pair hit</div>
      <div class="stat"><strong>{pct(eval_.hit10, eval_.scored)}</strong>top-10 pair hit</div>
      <div class="stat"><strong>{eval_.mrr.toFixed(3)}</strong>MRR</div>
      <div class="stat"><strong>{eval_.scored}</strong>events</div>
    </div>
    <p>
      <strong>Pair hit</strong> means the engine's #K pair (actor +
      doctrine, both correct simultaneously) matched at least one
      true (actor, doctrine) cross-product cell. The candidate space
      is 121 actors × 61 doctrines = <strong>7,381 possible pairs</strong>;
      random chance is 0.014%. The engine performs 2,500× better
      than random.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>How to read this — honest framing</h2>
    <p class="reading">
      <strong>This engine is NOT a strict upgrade over the single
      engines.</strong> Both engines score better in isolation —
      doctrine top-3 is 59.5%, actor top-5 is 59.3%. The joint metric
      ("pair hit") is fundamentally harder: actor AND doctrine must
      both be right.
    </p>
    <p>The joint engine's actual product value is different:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Confidence calibration.</strong> Pairs with high
        actor-score + high doctrine-score + high co-occurrence are
        the engine's high-confidence outputs. Pairs with high scores
        but zero co-occurrence get demoted — they're the engine's
        "novel claim" flag. <em>This is the layer analyst-grade
        tooling actually wants.</em>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Cross-checking.</strong> When actor and doctrine
        engines disagree (actor says A, doctrine says D, but (A, D)
        has zero training co-occurrence), the joint engine surfaces
        the disagreement. That flag is what makes a v0.1 analyst
        review-queue.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Per-state utility varies dramatically</strong> —
        the US case below is the example.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Per-state breakdown</h2>
    <table class="state-table">
      <thead>
        <tr><th>state</th><th>n</th><th>top-1</th><th>top-3</th><th>top-5</th><th>MRR</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {perState.map(([state, row]) => (
          <tr>
            <td><code>{state.toUpperCase()}</code></td>
            <td>{row.scored}</td>
            <td>{pct(row.hit1, row.scored)}</td>
            <td>{pct(row.hit3, row.scored)}</td>
            <td>{pct(row.hit5, row.scored)}</td>
            <td>{row.mrr.toFixed(3)}</td>
          </tr>
        ))}
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p class="reading">
      <strong>US 76.7% top-1</strong> is the headline finding. The
      US's (actor, doctrine) signatures are dense and stable — CNMF
      almost always pairs with NCS-2023's disrupt-and-dismantle pillar
      because every major US disruption operation has been tagged
      against that same doctrine. High co-occurrence makes the joint
      score very confident here. Other states are sparser, so the
      joint engine reverts toward the marginal product of the two
      single engines.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Confident hits</h2>
    <p>
      Top-1 correct predictions where the engine had high training
      co-occurrence backing the pair. These are the joint engine's
      best operating mode.
    </p>
    <table class="hits-table">
      <thead>
        <tr><th>date</th><th>event</th><th>predicted pair</th><th>co-occurrence</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {eval_.confidentHits.slice(0, 10).map((h) => (
          <tr>
            <td>{h.startDate ?? '????'}</td>
            <td><a href={`/event/${h.eventId}`}>{h.eventName}</a></td>
            <td>
              <a href={`/actor/${h.top5[0].actorId}`}>{actorName(h.top5[0].actorId)}</a>{' × '}
              <a href={`/doctrine/${h.top5[0].doctrineId}`}>{doctrineName(h.top5[0].doctrineId)}</a>
            </td>
            <td><strong>{h.top5[0].coOccurrence}</strong></td>
          </tr>
        ))}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Worst predictions</h2>
    <p>
      Where the engine confidently picked a popular pair when the
      correct answer was an outlier.
    </p>
    <table class="worst-table">
      <thead>
        <tr><th>rank</th><th>date</th><th>event</th><th>true</th><th>engine top-1</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {eval_.worst.slice(0, 10).map((w) => (
          <tr>
            <td>{w.bestRank}</td>
            <td>{w.startDate ?? '????'}</td>
            <td><a href={`/event/${w.eventId}`}>{w.eventName}</a></td>
            <td>
              {w.trueActors[0] && <><a href={`/actor/${w.trueActors[0]}`}>{actorName(w.trueActors[0])}</a> × <a href={`/doctrine/${w.trueDoctrines[0]}`}>{doctrineName(w.trueDoctrines[0] ?? '')}</a></>}
            </td>
            <td>
              {w.top5[0] && <><a href={`/actor/${w.top5[0].actorId}`}>{actorName(w.top5[0].actorId)}</a> × <a href={`/doctrine/${w.top5[0].doctrineId}`}>{doctrineName(w.top5[0].doctrineId)}</a></>}
            </td>
          </tr>
        ))}
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p class="reading">
      <strong>Reading.</strong> The repeated <em>APT41 × MCF</em>
      fallback in the worst-predictions list is the signature of
      defaulting to the most-common pair. When features don't strongly
      pull elsewhere, the engine reverts to the densest cell. That's
      a calibration issue — the prior weight on co-occurrence is
      probably too high.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>What this changes</h2>
    <p>
      We now have three engines operating on the same atlas:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Doctrine prediction</strong> — the primary "why"
        engine. Highest top-K rates. Use this as the analytic
        headline.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Actor attribution</strong> — the "who" engine.
        Useful for narrowing the candidate cluster.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Joint engine</strong> — the confidence and novelty
        layer. Not for headline ranking; for grading the other two
        engines' outputs and flagging novel attribution patterns.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      The right v0.1 product output for a live unattributed event:
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li>Doctrine engine top-3 (the "why" framing — 60% top-3 hit rate)</li>
      <li>Actor engine top-5 (the "who" shortlist — 59% top-5)</li>
      <li>Joint engine top-1 pair — only published when co-occurrence ≥ 2 (the "confident pattern" claim)</li>
      <li>Disagreement flag — fired when the joint top pair has zero co-occurrence (the "novel pattern" claim)</li>
    </ol>
    <p>Engine source: <code>src/utils/joint-prediction.ts</code>. JSON: <a href="/api/joint-eval.json">/api/joint-eval.json</a>.</p>
  </section>
</Base>

<style>
  .meta { color: var(--ctp-subtext0); font-size: 0.9375rem; margin: 0 0 1.5rem; }
  .stat-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(140px, 1fr));
    gap: 0.5rem;
    margin: 1rem 0 1.5rem;
  }
  .stat {
    display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 0.125rem;
    padding: 0.75rem 1rem;
    background: var(--ctp-mantle);
    border: 1px solid var(--ctp-surface0);
    border-radius: var(--radius-md);
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.75rem; color: var(--ctp-subtext1);
  }
  .stat strong { font-size: 1.5rem; color: var(--ctp-text); font-weight: 600; }
  table { border-collapse: collapse; width: 100%; font-size: 0.875rem; margin: 0.75rem 0 1rem; }
  th, td { text-align: left; padding: 0.375rem 0.625rem; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--ctp-surface0); vertical-align: top; }
  th { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 0.75rem; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.06em; color: var(--ctp-subtext0); }
  td { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 0.8125rem; }
  td a { color: var(--ctp-text); }
  td a:hover { color: var(--ctp-blue); }
  .worst-table td:first-child, .hits-table td:last-child { font-weight: 700; }
  .worst-table td:first-child { color: var(--ctp-peach); }
  .hits-table td:last-child { color: var(--ctp-green); }
  .reading {
    background: var(--ctp-mantle);
    border-left: 3px solid var(--ctp-blue);
    padding: 0.75rem 1rem;
    border-radius: var(--radius-sm);
    font-size: 0.9375rem;
    margin: 0.75rem 0;
  }
  ol li, ul li { margin: 0.4rem 0; }
</style>
